Intro

Air travel is becoming a ubiquitous part of modern life. with recent news of Boeing 747 having to make emergency landing because of issues with flight technology, I wanted to know how Plane type and operators, affected the fatalities and survivors.

Data Importing with Formatting dates

Air <- read_csv("Airplane_Crashes_and_Fatalities_Since_1908.csv", 
    col_types = cols(Date = col_date(format = "%m/%d/%Y")))

Cleaning

#Omiting NA 
Air$Fatalities[is.na(Air$Fatalities)] = 0

#Calculate Survivors
Air$Survived = Air$Aboard - Air$Fatalities

summary(Air$Survived)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.    NA's 
##   0.000   0.000   0.000   7.471   2.000 516.000      22

Exploratroty Graphs

dead_per_year = ggplot(Air, aes(Date, Fatalities)) +  
    geom_bar(na.rm = TRUE, stat="identity", position="identity", colour="purple") + scale_x_date() + xlab("Year") + ylab("Fatalities") + ggtitle("Dead Per Year")

crash_per_year = ggplot(Air, aes(Date)) +  
    geom_histogram(binwidth=1000, fill="lightblue", col="black") + 
    scale_x_date() + xlab("Year") + ylab("Crashes") + ggtitle("Planes crashed per year")

aboard_per_year = ggplot(Air, aes(Date, Aboard)) +  
    geom_bar(na.rm = TRUE, stat="identity", position="identity", colour="red") + scale_x_date() + xlab("Year") + ylab("Aboard") + ggtitle("People Aboard Per Year")

survived_per_year = ggplot(Air, aes(Date, Survived)) +  
    geom_bar(na.rm = TRUE, stat="identity", position="identity", colour="green") + scale_x_date() + xlab("Year") + ylab("Aboard") + ggtitle("People Survived Per Year")

grid.arrange(crash_per_year, aboard_per_year, dead_per_year, survived_per_year, ncol=2)

For the next visuals I wanted to look at top 25 Fatalities by Plane Type,Crashes by Operator,Crashes by Plane Type. To do so I aggragate data here to plot and visualize later

#Fatalities by Plane Type
plane_type = aggregate(Air$Fatalities, by=list(Type=Air$Type), FUN=sum)
names(plane_type) = c("Type", "Fatalities")
plane_type = plane_type[ order(-plane_type$Fatalities), ]

# Crashes by Operator
data.operator = Air['Operator']
data.operator = data.frame(table(data.operator))
data.operator = data.operator[-c(1),]
data.operator = data.operator[ order(-data.operator$Freq), ]


# Crashes by Plane Type
data.type = Air['Type']
data.type = data.frame(table(data.type))
data.type = data.type[-c(1),]
data.type = data.type[ order(-data.type$Freq), ]
ggplot(plane_type[1:25,], aes(x=reorder(factor(Type), Fatalities), y=Fatalities, alpha=Fatalities)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill="red") + 
  xlab("Plane Type") + 
  ylab("Fatalities") + 
  ggtitle("Top 25 Plane Types with the most Fatalities") + 
  coord_flip()

ggplot(data.type[1:25,], aes(x=reorder(factor(data.type), Freq), y=Freq, alpha=Freq)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill="green") + 
  xlab("Plane Type") + 
  ylab("Number of Crashes") + 
  ggtitle("Top 25 Plane Types with the most Crashes") + 
  coord_flip()

stripchart(Air$Fatalities ~ Air$Date, main='Fatalities by Date', ylab='Fatalities', xlab='Date', method='jitter', pch=19, col=gray(0.4), vertical=TRUE)

# Plot "Accidents and Fatalities by Year"
ggplot(Air, aes(x = Date, y = Fatalities, fill = Survived)) + geom_bar(stat = "identity") + ggtitle("Accidents and Fatalities by Year")

Methods and Materials

Mechanical tasks Interpret the ANOVA table for the model. Test for the presence of interaction between the two explanatory variables both graphically and statistically.

ANOVA

Using a numerical response variable, and two categorical explanatory variables. Use deviance coding with contr.sum. (was not useful for my data set due to my dataframe not having factor variables)

Air2 <- Air
Air2$Type<- factor(Air2$Type)
contrasts(Air2$Type) = "contr.sum"
Air2$Operator<- factor(Air2$Operator)
contrasts(Air2$Operator) = "contr.sum"
Air2$Survived <- factor(Air2$Survived)
contrasts(Air2$Survived) = "contr.sum"
Airlm2<-lm(Aboard ~ Fatalities + Type:Survived, data = Air)
head_print(Airlm2, n = 20)

Interpreting the ANOVA table for the model.

Using the total number of people on board by, the total number of fatalities, plus the type of plane that crashed. We can see that fatalities has a higher f value than our F statistic, and is shown to be significant in predicting the ammount of people who were on board, in the airplane crash data set. Type is also significant, but not as much as Fatalities.

Discussion

This is historical plane crash data, as such each row of data was an individual plane crash. It is not probable that one could use this dataset to predict future plane crashes.

As you can see from all three of my models above, I have very wide data, each entery is an individual incident, and I would love more context about the incidents to deduce anything. However this has taught me that methods such as simple Linear regression are suitable for predicting the Aboard passengers given Fattalities, however when it comes to multiple regression, neither additive, nor interactive models for variables such as type, operator, and location. Only Type was suitable for multiple regression.
